#. type: Plain text
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/virtualization/_index.adoc:140
#: documentation/content/en/books/handbook/virtualization/_index.adoc:246
#, fuzzy
msgid "Create a New Kernel Configuration File"
msgstr ""
"创建一个新的内核配置文件\n"
"\n"
"To create a new kernel configuration file, follow these steps:\n"
"\n"
"1. Navigate to the directory where the kernel source code is located.\n"
"\n"
"2. Copy the existing kernel configuration file, typically named \"config\" or \"defconfig\", to a new file name. For example, you can use the command `cp config myconfig` to create a new config file called \"myconfig\".\n"
"\n"
"3. Open the newly created configuration file in a text editor or with a command-line tool such as `vi` or `nano`.\n"
"\n"
"4. Make any necessary changes to the configuration options. You can enable or disable various kernel features and modules by modifying the corresponding lines in the configuration file.\n"
"\n"
"5. Save the changes and exit the text editor or command-line tool.\n"
"\n"
"6. Run the command `make oldconfig` to update the configuration, taking into account any new options or changes made since the original configuration file was created.\n"
"\n"
"7. Build the kernel using the updated configuration file. You can do this by running the command `make` or `make bzImage` depending on the specific build process of your kernel.\n"
"\n"
"Once the kernel has been built, you can install it and use the new configuration by following the appropriate steps for your specific operating system or distribution."

